\f + \fr 17:1\ft Year of the World 2960, Year before Christ 1044.\f*
\f + \fr 17:1\ft Cedar. Such were esteemed the most magnificent, ver. 6. See 2 Kings vii.\f*
\f + \fr 17:9\ft A place permanent and secure, while I have had no fixed abode. (Calmet) --- No more, for a long time: and unless they provoke me by their crimes, as they did afterwards, and were exposed to more severe chastisements. Constant rest is not always expedient. (Tirinus)\f*
\f + \fr 17:11\ft Seed, even till Christ shall be born of the Blessed Virgin, of the family of David.\f*
\f + \fr 17:12\ft Ever often means only a long duration. The dominion of Christ shall have no end. (Calmet) --- The Church founded by this true David, (Haydock) falls heir to these promises. (Du Hamel)\f*
\f + \fr 17:13\ft Thee. The posterity of Saul lost the throne. (Haydock) --- If Solomon was reprobated, his children were permitted to reign. It is also presumed that he did penance; though this is not certain.\f*
\f + \fr 17:17\ft Men. Who was ever more favoured by God than David? Hebrew, "Thou hast regarded me according to the estate of a man of high degree." (Protestants) (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 17:18\ft Known him. Treating him with love and tenderness, as a friend. How can David sufficiently testify his gratitude?\f*
\f + \fr 17:21\ft Himself. Hebrew adds, "and to make thee a name."\f*
\f + \fr 17:27\ft Begun. Hebrew, "be pleased, (Haydock) or thou hast had the goodness to bless." Syriac, "I pray thee bless."\f*
